DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(92)90021-B
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969290021B
AB  - Import-competing industries in many democracies can pursue import relief via administered protection (AP) procedures or can lobby politicians directly. In this paper an industry chooses the option that maximizes expected profits. Both the AP and lobbying processes required a fixed resource cost and have an associated subjective probability of success. We show that policy reforms that decrease the probability of success under administered protection or lobbying may reduce expected national welfare when both processes are potentially profitable.
